For centuries, Monaco was known for attracting many wealthy and European royalties due to its gambling scene. Tournaments and cruises sailors, gamblers and card sharks from all over the world flooded Monaco. But as the years went by, gambling was increasingly given a bad reputation, study after study with suggested correlations between gambling and social problems became increasingly common, and eventually, casinos were considered evil.

Newer, lighter, and therefore more damaging schemes such as stock market speculation were developed, and centuries-old gambling houses were quickly replaced by huge casinos operating online with bewildering technology. By the time the decades passed, Monaco was no longer known for its shuttered gambling houses but rather for tax benefits and a tax-free environment. However, Monaco has also experienced changes in modern times. In the early 20 th century, when the gambling arena expanded to contribute to the state’s gross domestic product, it became a mainstream industry. This means that anyone editorializing the Monaco gambling industry these days usually focuses on the benefits it brings to the country’s economy.

In the last 20 years, Monaco’s gambling industry has made big strides to maintain its world-class status. With new techniques and software, online gambling has now become a much-needed and highly efficient industry in the region. This year, Monaco joined the efforts of the United Nations World Tourism Organization (UNWTO) that was designed to make the world a more responsible travel destination by promoting sustainable tourism and “responsible travel” initiatives.
